<subSubSection pageId="3" pageNumber="114" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1436,151,285]" pageId="3" pageNumber="114">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,315,151,177]" pageId="3" pageNumber="114">Remarks.</emphasis>
Using the key in 
<bibRefCitation author="Negrobov, O. P. &amp; Stackelberg, A. A." box="[516,870,151,177]" pageId="3" pageNumber="114" pagination="347 - 354" refId="ref9162" refString="Negrobov, O. P. &amp; Stackelberg, A. A. (1971 - 77) 29. Dolichopodidae. Medeterinae. In: Lindner, E. (Ed.), Die Fliegen der Palaearktischen Region, 4 (5), Lief. 284, 289, 302, 303, 316, 238 - 256 (1971), 257 - 302 (1972), 303 - 324 (1974), 325 - 346 (1974), 347 - 354 (1977). [in German]" type="journal article" year="1971">Negrobov &amp; Stackelberg (1971</bibRefCitation>
–77), the new species runs to 
<taxonomicName authority="Wood" authorityName="Wood" authorityYear="1913" box="[1205,1432,151,177]" class="Insecta" family="Dolichopodidae" genus="Thrypticus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="114" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="nigricauda">
<emphasis box="[1205,1356,151,177]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="114">T. nigricauda</emphasis>
Wood
</taxonomicName>
, but can be distinguished by the characters given in the key below. The male genitalia resemble that of 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Strobl" baseAuthorityYear="1880" box="[1329,1436,187,213]" class="Insecta" family="Dolichopodidae" genus="Thrypticus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="114" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="divisus">
<emphasis box="[1329,1436,187,213]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="114">T. divisus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation box="[160,245,223,249]" captionStart="FIGURE 8" captionStartId="12.[151,250,1597,1621]" captionTargetBox="[159,1430,411,1564]" captionTargetId="figure-509@12.[151,1436,403,1573]" captionTargetPageId="12" captionText="FIGURE 8. Thrypticus species, hypopygia left lateral. A, T. nigricauda Wood; B, T. divisus Strobl; C, T. laetus Verrall; D, T. altaicus Negrobov; E, T. virescens Negrobov; F, T. politus Negrobov. (Figs from Negrobov &amp; Stackelberg (1971–77))." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4411655" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4411655/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="114">Fig. 8B</figureCitation>
) but the new species is lacking an ad seta on the mid tibia and the apex of the surstylus is almost triangular and without notches.
</paragraph>
